WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.360
Hi, I'm Nicola, and I want to talk to you about translating your Shiny app into multiple

00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:16.360
languages. Some of you might be disappointed because when I say multiple languages in Shiny

00:00:16.360 --> 00:00:22.280
apps, I'm talking about spoken languages, not programming languages today. Since I'm

00:00:22.280 --> 00:00:25.160
basically going to spend the next couple of minutes telling you how annoying it was to

00:00:25.160 --> 00:00:28.959
develop a Shiny app in multiple languages, I thought I'd start by telling you why it's

00:00:28.959 --> 00:00:35.240
actually a worthwhile thing to do. The vast majority of websites and apps, not just Shiny

00:00:35.240 --> 00:00:40.080
apps, are developed in English. The problem with this is that the vast majority of people

00:00:40.080 --> 00:00:45.080
don't speak English. Only around 2 in 11 people actually speak English, and that's a large

00:00:45.080 --> 00:00:51.439
number of people that automatically exclude from interacting with your Shiny app. Language

00:00:51.439 --> 00:00:55.720
selectors are becoming more commonplace in traditional web development, and we want to

00:00:55.720 --> 00:01:04.239
make sure that Shiny apps don't get left behind. Having said that, translating Shiny

00:01:04.239 --> 00:01:13.239
apps into multiple languages is not that straightforward to do. What I want to talk about today is

00:01:13.239 --> 00:01:19.000
some of the small issues that cropped up when we were developing a bilingual Shiny app to

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:25.680
present public data. Translation affects every single component of your Shiny app. Simple

00:01:25.680 --> 00:01:32.000
UI elements suddenly became reactive expressions that relied on a user input. There are a couple

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:36.559
of packages out there that help you to automate the translation process, but what we found

00:01:36.559 --> 00:01:41.680
is that those packages typically only work for a few of the most widely spoken languages,

00:01:41.680 --> 00:01:46.400
and that their built-in dictionaries typically didn't include domain-specific terms. So when

00:01:46.400 --> 00:01:50.919
we were developing our bilingual app, we built the translation capabilities directly into

00:01:50.919 --> 00:01:56.599
the app itself. And during the development process, there were a couple of seemingly

00:01:56.599 --> 00:02:01.320
small problems that suddenly became much bigger problems to face. And one of those problems

00:02:01.320 --> 00:02:08.600
was what we thought was easy, ordering a factor for a bar chart. Most of you have probably

00:02:08.600 --> 00:02:13.839
come across the fact that R, in the absence of other instructions, will automatically

00:02:13.839 --> 00:02:18.600
sort your character vectors and your factors alphabetically. However, this doesn't always

00:02:18.600 --> 00:02:25.440
make sense. So in this example here, we have age group encodings as character strings,

00:02:25.440 --> 00:02:29.639
and we might want to sort them from young to old because that's easier for a user to

00:02:29.639 --> 00:02:34.000
interpret. So for a single language, this is really easy, right? We just create a factor

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:41.080
and we explicitly set the factor level. And we get a nicely ordered bar chart. The problem

00:02:41.080 --> 00:02:47.320
is that when we start doing this with multiple languages, it's not quite so easy. First of

00:02:47.320 --> 00:02:51.800
all, we can't rely on this alphabetical ordering at all anymore. If we sort character vector

00:02:51.800 --> 00:02:55.360
in one language and we sort it in another, actually they're still in different orders

00:02:55.360 --> 00:03:00.960
now. So we can't rely on alphabetical ordering at all. We also don't want to have to manually

00:03:00.960 --> 00:03:05.960
specify factor levels for all languages. It's a little bit annoying if you have a few words

00:03:05.960 --> 00:03:10.399
in two languages, but if you have hundreds or thousands of words in multiple languages,

00:03:10.399 --> 00:03:16.199
it's just completely unmanageable. So to solve this problem for our app, what we did was

00:03:16.199 --> 00:03:21.360
we ended up using a sort of default or primary language for everything related to data processing.

00:03:21.360 --> 00:03:27.039
So in our case, we did everything in English and we explicitly set these factor levels

00:03:27.039 --> 00:03:32.440
in English only. For our bar chart example, what that meant was essentially creating two

00:03:32.440 --> 00:03:38.600
different functions. One function to compute the break point for the x axis. Again, this

00:03:38.600 --> 00:03:43.639
is done in English only based on our dataset. We then created a second function to compute

00:03:43.639 --> 00:03:47.600
the labels based on the output from that breaks function and from the user's choice

00:03:47.600 --> 00:03:57.720
of language. Essentially, we wanted to translate as little as possible. So I hope the last

00:03:57.720 --> 00:04:01.600
few minutes have convinced you that translating Shiny app, although it's not straightforward,

00:04:01.600 --> 00:04:07.399
it is a very useful and worthwhile thing to do. What we found our sort of biggest lesson

00:04:07.399 --> 00:04:11.080
was that when we were building this app, translation was always the first problem that we actually

00:04:11.080 --> 00:04:16.440
had to think about if we wanted to add something new. But to keep our app actually efficient,

00:04:16.440 --> 00:04:21.959
it was always the last one. So I hope it's been useful. Find me on Twitter if you want

00:04:21.959 --> 00:04:22.640
to ask questions.

